<paper id="1496572999"><title>On Generating Solved Instances of Computational Problems</title><year>1988</year><authors><author org="Columbia University" id="2162106674">Martín Abadi</author><author org="DEC Systems Research Center" id="2091164281">Eric Allender</author><author org="Columbia University" id="2777912906">Andrei Z. Broder</author><author org="Rutgers University" id="2632998863">Joan Feigenbaum</author><author org="AT&amp;T Bell Lab.#TAB#" id="2677968834">Lane A. Hemachandra</author></authors><n_citation>21</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>1498590645</reference><reference>2011039300</reference><reference>2021320809</reference><reference>2051283034</reference><reference>2099188893</reference><reference>2100008268</reference><reference>2107324709</reference><reference>2111728769</reference><reference>2148043549</reference><reference>2150780437</reference><reference>2151433956</reference><reference>2152005134</reference><reference>2741949592</reference></references><venue id="1153524033" type="C">International Cryptology Conference</venue><doi>10.1007/0-387-34799-2_23</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.47098">Discrete mathematics</keyword><keyword weight="0.55473">Computational problem</keyword><keyword weight="0.57236">Kolmogorov complexity</keyword><keyword weight="0.46846">Algebra</keyword><keyword weight="0.44089">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.4466">Witness</keyword><keyword weight="0.6299">Turing machine</keyword><keyword weight="0.42459">Adversary</keyword><keyword weight="0.48419">Computation</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, New York, NY</publisher><abstract>We consider the efficient generation of solved instances of computational problems. In particular, we consider invulnerable generators. Let S be a subset of 0,1* and M be a Turing Machine that accepts S; an accepting computation w of M on input x is called a “witness” that x ∈ S. Informally, a program is an α-invulnerable generator if, on input 1n, it produces instance-witness pairs , with |x| = n, according to a distribution under which any polynomial-time adversary who is given x fails to find a witness that x ∈ S, with probability at least α, for infinitely many lengths n.</abstract></paper>